eden","BEF 20 SEP 1306":"vóór 20 september 1306","1230":"1230","1263":"1263","1261":"1261","1249":"1249","1225":"1225","1246":"1246","about 1306":"circa 1306","1245":"1245","1310":"1310","about 1245":"circa 1245","about 1263":"circa 1263","1306":"1306","Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom":"Wiltshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Hatch, Somerset, England":"Hatch, Somerset, England","Hatch, Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom":"Hatch, Wiltshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Świętokrzyskie, Poland":"świętokrzyskie, Polen"},"en":{"about 1245–about 1306":"about 1245–about 1306","1245–1306":"1245–1306","1246–1310":"1246–1310","1261–Female":"1261–Deceased","1263–Female":"1263–Deceased","1225–Male":"1225–Deceased","1230–Female":"1230–Deceased","BEF 20 SEP 1306":"before 20 September 1306","1230":"1230","1263":"1263","1261":"1261","1249":"1249","1225":"1225","1246":"1246","about 1306":"about 1306","1245":"1245","1310":"1310","about 1245":"about 1245","about 1263":"about 1263","1306":"1306","Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom":"Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom","Hatch, Somerset, England":"Hatch, Somerset, England","Hatch, Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom":"Hatch, Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom","Świętokrzyskie, Poland":"świętokrzyskie, Poland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Beauchamp","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Antoine, Jacques, Yves, Andre, Armand, Emile, Fernand, Marcel, Marthe, Remi, Alcide, Camille.","English (of Norman origin) and French: habitational name from any of several places in France, for example in Manche and Somme, that are named with Old French <i>beu</i>, <i>bel</i> ‘fair, lovely’ + <i>champ(s)</i> ‘field, plain’ (from Latin <i>bello campo</i> ‘beautiful field’). In English the surname is generally pronounced   Beecham  . Compare   Bushaw  .","English: in some cases, an Anglo-Norman French adaptation of Scottish   Campbell  , by translation into French of the folk etymology <i>de campo bello</i> ‘from the fair field’."],"variants":[{"name":"Beecham","meanings":["English (Lincolnshire): variant of   Beauchamp  , reflecting the normal English pronunciation."]},{"name":"Beachem","meanings":["English (Somerset and Gloucestershire): variant of   Beauchamp  ."]},{"name":"Beachum","meanings":["Altered form of English   Beauchamp  ."]},{"name":"Bagent","meanings":["English:","possibly a colloquial pronunciation of   Beauchamp   or   Beecham  . Old French <i>Beau-</i> often appears as <i>Be(e)-</i> in English surnames. The <i>-ch-</i> has been voiced and excrescent <i>-t</i> has been added.","perhaps an Anglicized form of a French or Flemish surname such as <b>Beaujean</b> and <b>Bejean</b>, from Old French <i>bel Jehan</i> ‘handsome John’ + excrescent <i>-t</i>. It could have been introduced to England in the 15th or 16th century by Flemish migrants."]},{"name":"Beacham","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Beauchamp  ."]},{"name":"Campbell","meanings":["Scottish: nickname from Gaelic <i>cam</i> ‘crooked, bent’ + <i>beul</i> ‘mouth’. As a result of folk etymology, the surname was often represented in Latin documents as <i>de bello campo</i> ‘of the fair field’, which led to the name sometimes being ‘translated’ into Anglo-Norman French as   Beauchamp  .","Irish (North Armagh): adopted for Gaelic <b>Mac Cathmhaoil</b> ‘son of Cathmhaol’ (literally ‘battle chief’): see   Caulfield   and   Cowell  .","English: variant of   Camel  , under the influence of the Scottish name (see 1 above)."]},{"name":"Bushaw","meanings":["Americanized form of French   Beauchamp   and   Bouchard  ."]},{"name":"Beacom","meanings":["English (Somerset) and Irish (Fermanagh): of Norman origin, a variant of   Beauchamp  ."]}]},{"name":"Eustace","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the Old French form of the Late Greek names <i>Eustakhios</i> and <i>Eustathios</i>. These were evidently of separate origin, the former derived from <i>eu</i> ‘well, good’ + <i>stakhys</i> ‘grapes’, the latter from <i>eu</i> + <i>stēnai</i> ‘to stand’. However, the tradition is very confused. The name was introduced in this form to Britain by the Normans, among whom it was popular as a result of the fame of  St Eustace , a Norman nobleman who was said to have been converted to Christianity by the vision of a crucifix between the antlers of the stag he was hunting."],"variants":[]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of the various boys' names with the first syllable <i>Ed-</i>, especially   Edward ."],"variants":[{"name":"Edward","meanings":["From an Old English personal name derived from <i>ēad</i> ‘prosperity, riches’ + <i>weard</i> ‘guard’. This has been one of the most successful of all Old English names, in frequent use from before the Conquest to the present day, and even being exported into other European languages. It was the name of three Anglo-Saxon kings and has been borne by eight kings of England since the Norman Conquest. It is also the name of the youngest son of  Queen Elizabeth II . The most influential early bearer was  King Edward  the Confessor (  ?1002–66 ; ruled  1042–66 ). In a troubled period of English history, he contrived to rule fairly and (for a time at any rate) firmly. But in the latter part of his reign he paid more attention to his religion than to his kingdom. He died childless, and his death sparked off conflicting claims to his throne, which were resolved by the victory of William the Conqueror at the Battle of Hastings. His memory was honoured by Normans and English alike, for his fairness and his piety. Edward's mother was Norman; he had spent part of his youth in Normandy; and William claimed to have been nominated by Edward as his successor. Edward was canonized in the 12th century, and came to be venerated throughout Europe as a model of a Christian king."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Baron Eustace de Beauchamp de Hache was born about 1245, in Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Robert de Beauchamp lord of Hache, was 21 and his mother, Juliane de Wyly, was 16. He had at least 2 daughters with Amice Lowe Baroness Hache. He died about 1306, in świętokrzyskie, Poland, at the age of 63."},"et":{"about 1245–about 1306":"umbes 1245–umbes 1306","1245–1306":"1245–1306","1246–1310":"1246–1310","1261–Female":"1261–Surnud","1263–Female":"1263–Surnud","1225–Male":"1225–Surnud","1230–Female":"1230–Surnud","BEF 20 SEP 1306":"enne 20. septembrit 1306","1230":"1230","1263":"1263","1261":"1261","1249":"1249","1225":"1225","1246":"1246","about 1306":"umbes 1306","1245":"1245","1310":"1310","about 1245":"umbes 1245","about 1263":"umbes 1263","1306":"1306","Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom":"Wiltshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Hatch, Somerset, England":"Hatch, Somerset, England","Hatch, Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom":"Hatch, Wiltshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Świętokrzyskie, Poland":"świętokrzyskie, Poola"},"fi":{"about 1245–about 1306":"noin 1245–noin 1306","1245–1306":"1245–1306","1246–1310":"1246–1310","1261–Female":"1261–Kuollut","1263–Female":"1263–Kuollut","1225–Male":"1225–Kuollut","1230–Female":"1230–Kuollut","BEF 20 SEP 1306":"ennen vuotta 20. syyskuuta 1306","1230":"1230","1263":"1263","1261":"1261","1249":"1249","1225":"1225","1246":"1246","about 1306":"noin 1306","1245":"1245","1310":"1310","about 1245":"noin 1245","about 1263":"noin 1263","1306":"1306","Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom":"Wiltshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Hatch, Somerset, England":"Hatch, Somerset, England","Hatch, Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom":"Hatch, Wiltshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Świętokrzyskie, Poland":"świętokrzyskie, Puola"},"fr":{"about 1245–about 1306":"environ 1245–environ 1306","1245–1306":"1245